SIMPLE: antinomian
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Antinomian
<hw>An`ti*no"mi*an</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Antimony</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to the Antinomians;
opposed to the doctrine that the moral law is obligatory.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Antinomian</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Antinomian
<hw>An`ti*no"mi*an</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One
who maintains that, under the gospel dispensation, the moral law is of
no use or obligation, but that faith alone is necessary to salvation.
The sect of Antinomians originated with John Agricola, in Germany, about
the year 1535.</def> <rj><au>Mosheim.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Antinomianism</ent>⟦br⟧
